 Castle, Durham, England":"Durham, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Northumberland, England, United Kingdom":"Northumberland, England"},"en":{"1126–1176":"1126–1176","1144–1247":"1144–1247","1170–1220":"1170–1220","1177–1223":"1177–1223","1121–1150":"1121–1150","1105–Female":"1105–Deceased","1105":"1105","1126":"1126","1247":"1247","1169":"1169","1223":"1223","1177":"1177","1144":"1144","1176":"1176","1121":"1121","1220":"1220","1150":"1150","1170":"1170","Bansborough, Northumberland, England":"Northumberland, England, United Kingdom","Northumberland, England":"Northumberland, England","Etherstone Castle, Durham, England":"Durham, England, United Kingdom","Northumberland, England, United Kingdom":"Northumberland, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Forester","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Scottish: variant of   Forrester   (see   Forrest  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Forrester","meanings":["English: occupational name from Middle English <i>forester</i> ‘officer in charge of a forest or lord's hunting ground’ (Old French <i>forestier</i>, Anglo-Norman <i>forester</i>). See   Forrest  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir William Foreste